*** Getting the Size of a Directory

du -sh /home/Documents
=>
188k  /home/Documents


----------------------------------------------------------------------
sudo du -shc /var/*
=>
24K	/var/db
4.0K	/var/empty
4.0K	/var/games
77G	/var/lib
4.0K	/var/local
0	/var/lock

----------------------------------------------------------------------
*** Get a report about the disk usage of the first-level subdirectories is to use the --max-depth option:

sudo du -h --max-depth=1 /var
=>
77G	  /var/lib
24K	  /var/db
4.0K	/var/empty
4.0K	/var/local
4.0K	/var/opt
196K	/var/spool

----------------------------------------------------------------------
By default, the du command shows the disk space used by the directory or file. To find the apparent size of a directory, use the --apparent-size option. The â€œapparent sizeâ€ of a file is how much data is actually in the file.

sudo du -sh --apparent-size /var

----------------------------------------------------------------------

sort the directories by their size and then pipe the output to the head command that will print only the top 5 directories:

sudo du -h /var/ | sort -rh | head -5
=>
85G	/var/
77G	/var/lib
75G	/var/lib/libvirt/images
